- 1 -

harmonic distortion on utility systems, heat and exhaust discharge, vibration, and a level
of continuous noise that may exceed legally permitted residential levels. This part is
intended to ensure that communities receive meaningful protections without imposing an
outright ban on digital asset mining activities, and that operators willing to meet modern
professional standards retain a clear, objective pathway to approval.
7-51-2802. Part definitions.
As used in this part:
(1) "Digital asset mining facility" means a group of computers working at
a single site that consume more than one megawatt (1 MW) of energy on an
average annual basis for the purpose of securing a blockchain protocol and
generating controllable electronic records;
(2) "Nuisance quarry" means a proposed quarry that meets all of the
following conditions:
(A) The real property on which the proposed quarry is to be
established consists of less than two hundred (200) contiguous acres;
and
(B) The proposed quarry has setbacks of less than five hundred
feet (500') between the boundary of active mining or extraction activity
and any existing residential dwelling; and
(3) "Quarry":
(A) Means a site that hosts the extraction, removal, and
mechanized processing of stone, gravel, phosphate rock, metallic ore,
limestone, marble, chert, sand, dimension stone, or any other solid
mineral or substance of commercial value, except coal mining,
underground stone mining, and deep metal mining, including, but not
limited to, zinc, found in natural deposits in the earth, for barter or sale;
and
- 2 - 016184

(B) Does not include the excavation or removal of material that is
incidental to the construction of a subterranean tunnel or system of
subterranean tunnels designed primarily for the transportation of
passengers and goods using electric, autonomous, or low-emission
vehicles, or other emerging technology for vehicles and transportation
systems, where the tunnels are constructed at depths sufficient to avoid
interference with surface uses.
7-51-2803. Local approval of quarry or digital asset mining facilities.
(a) Prior to a nuisance quarry or digital asset mining facility being established in
a county, municipality, or metropolitan government, the local legislative body for the
jurisdiction must approve the location for such facility by resolution in a public meeting.
(b) A local legislative body shall provide at least twenty-one (21) calendar days'
notice of the time and place of any meeting called pursuant to subsection (a) by:
(1) Publishing the notice in a newspaper of general circulation in the
county;
(2) Posting the notice on the local legislative body's official website;
(3) Posting the notice in at least three (3) places at the location where the
proposed nuisance quarry or digital asset mining facility will be established; and
(4) Sending the notice by first-class mail to each resident whose property
is within one thousand five hundred feet (1,500') of the property line of the
proposed location.
7-51-2804. Objective proof requirements.
(a) A local legislative body shall base its decision to approve or disapprove the
siting of a nuisance quarry or digital asset mining facility in a county, municipality, or
metropolitan government solely upon compliance with the requirements of this part and
the material evidence submitted pursuant to this section.
- 3 - 016184

(b) An applicant seeking to establish a nuisance quarry or a digital asset mining
facility shall submit to the local legislative body:
(1) Proof of adequate power, water, and sewer capacity, supported by
written confirmations from the applicable utilities. Any supporting engineering
analysis must be prepared and stamped by a professional engineer licensed in
this state;
(2) A traffic impact study, prepared and certified by a qualified
transportation engineer, demonstrating that projected vehicle movements can be
accommodated without materially degrading roadway safety or performance;
(3) An environmental study, prepared by a qualified environmental
professional, addressing noise, dust, vibration, and other material impacts on
surrounding property and natural resources;
(4) A baseline noise survey and an operational noise-management plan,
including reasonable monitoring mechanisms demonstrating that noise levels will
not exceed eighty A-weighted decibels (80 dBA), when measured at the property
boundary of the nuisance quarry or digital asset mining facility. Compliance with
this standard is determined using a twenty-four-hour equivalent continuous
sound level measurement, conducted in accordance with generally accepted
sound level measurement practices and using a properly calibrated sound level
meter;
(5) A stormwater and erosion-control plan meeting all applicable state
and local requirements that is prepared by a civil engineer licensed in this state;
(6) A reclamation or decommissioning plan appropriate to the proposed
operation, along with a cost estimate prepared by a licensed engineer. The
applicant shall secure financial assurance in a form acceptable to the local
legislative body to ensure completion of the plan upon closure; and
- 4 - 016184

(7) Sufficient financial and insurance documentation to demonstrate
operational capability and long-term stability, including ensuring that an
insurance policy meets reasonable minimum standards set by the local
legislative body, if such applicant is not a publicly traded company or has an
annual revenue of less than twenty-five million dollars ($25,000,000).
(c) In addition to the requirements of subsection (b):
(1) An applicant seeking to establish a digital asset mining facility shall
provide a study describing the facility's heat output, exhaust characteristics, and
any potential electrical interference. The study must demonstrate that the facility
will not adversely affect neighboring operations or utility systems; and
(2) An applicant seeking to establish a nuisance quarry shall post a bond
sufficient to cover projected roadway wear caused by truck traffic during
operations, in an amount determined by the local legislative body, if the applicant
is not a publicly traded company or has an annual revenue of less than twenty-
five million dollars ($25,000,000).
7-51-2805. Exemption.
This part does not apply to:
(1) Borrow material or borrow excavations, including rock borrow, dirt
borrow, solid rock borrow, graded solid rock borrow, or any similar material
meeting the department of transportation standard specifications for road and
bridge construction, whether temporary or project specific, and whether located
on or off the project site, when such material is used solely for a construction
project located within this state;
(2) An active or inactive quarry for which a mine identification number
was applied for or obtained from the mine safety and health administration of the
United States department of labor at any time prior to July 1, 2026;
- 5 - 016184

(3) An application or other request for approval submitted to the
appropriate local legislative body, or local building or codes enforcement
department, zoning authority, health department, or similar local department or
agency, related to the commencement, expansion, or resumption of mining
activity with respect to a quarry or mining operation that was active or that filed
an application for such a permit or approval from such a local legislative body or
department or agency at any time prior to July 1, 2026; or
(4) A proposed quarry or mining operation if an application has been
submitted to the department of environment and conservation for a stormwater
discharge permit, wastewater discharge permit, or air pollution control permit
related to the commencement, expansion, or resumption of activity at a quarry or
mining operation; provided, that the quarry or mining operation was active or had
submitted an application for such permit or approval to the department prior to
July 1, 2026.
SECTION 2. This act takes effect July 1, 2026, the public welfare requiring it, and,
except as expressly stated in this act, applies to any proposed nuisance quarry or digital asset
mining facility that will be established on or after that date.
